          "title": "Closing benediction: undivided hearts before an utterly faithful God (8:54-61)",
          "body": "Solomon rises from his knees and turns again to the assembly. He begins with doxology: 'Blessed be the LORD, who has given rest to His people Israel, according to all that He promised; not one word has failed' (8:56). The sweep of this declaration is enormous — every promise God made through Moses is certified as fulfilled at this moment. Joshua 21:45 uses nearly identical language, and now Solomon extends the verdict to include the Temple itself. From this foundation of proven divine faithfulness, Solomon prays two petitions for the congregation: that God may be with them as with the fathers, not leaving or forsaking them (8:57); and that He may incline their hearts to walk in His ways (8:58). The second petition is theologically significant — Solomon does not merely command Israel to obey; he asks God to move their hearts toward obedience. Human will and divine initiative are held together, not opposed. The stated purpose of the entire enterprise reaches its apex at 8:60: 'so that all the peoples of the earth may know that the LORD is God; there is no one else.' The dedication of the Temple has a universal missionary horizon. Solomon closes with the command that follows from everything: 'Let your heart therefore be wholly devoted (*shalem*) to the LORD our God' (8:61). The word *shalem* — complete, undivided, at peace — is the moral challenge the whole chapter has been building toward."
